00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:08.690
WENDY LI: In some
ways I kind of see

00:02:08.690 --> 00:02:10.480
my work in the
Woodrow Wilson School

00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:13.860
as being completely
opposite from my work

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:14.940
in the visual arts.


00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:17.010
And I think the
two work very well

00:02:17.010 --> 00:02:18.880
and are sort of symmetrical.


00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:22.870
This project I think really
sort of distills a lot

00:02:22.870 --> 00:02:26.430
of what we think of as
abstract political ideas.

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:30.650
We think of economic
reform as a very abstract

00:02:30.650 --> 00:02:33.130
political economic idea.


00:02:33.130 --> 00:02:36.230
We think of migration
also as a very sort

00:02:36.230 --> 00:02:39.140
of abstract
international concept.

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:40.970
What a lot of people
don't realize, I think,

00:02:40.970 --> 00:02:43.910
especially, is that these are
very real human things that

00:02:43.910 --> 00:02:45.950
are happening and they're
real human experiences.

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:49.580
And so even though I spent so
much time in the Wilson School

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:53.150
going through data sets, combing
through international relations

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:57.090
theory and political
philosophy, a lot of it

00:02:57.090 --> 00:03:00.000
still doesn't really matter
until you tie it back

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:01.810
to real people.


00:03:01.810 --> 00:03:04.310
Most people would be
able to see these photos

00:03:04.310 --> 00:03:08.260
and instantly recognize that
they're personal photos.

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:10.180
A lot of people will
look at these photographs

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:12.500
